narratives.question_text: What knowledge, skills, and insights did you develop by taking this course?
comments: This is such an awesome course for those in the arts not looking to be fed answers about what art is to them and curating their own opinions, critiques, etc. while engaging with all genres of dance

I learned more about dance and how it has been used historically in a political matter.  I also learned about major figures in (political) dance history like Alvin Ailey, Katherine Dunham, Camille A. Brown, etc.

narratives.question_text: What are the strengths and weaknesses of this course and how could it be improved?
comments:
Strengths: always received a lot of helpful feedback!
Weaknesses: Sometimes I feel like the class felt disjointed week to week

The strengths of this course were that it was a seminar and we got to talk about and debate the dances we saw.  The environment was safe to express my opinion and I never felt my views were inadequate because I'm not a dancer. We also got to see Yvonne Rainer's show "What About the Bees?" in NYC for free!  I think sometimes the readings were a bit much and sometimes we would not get to all of them which was a tad annoying but when we told Prof. Reid, some of them got reduced.

narratives.question_text: Would you recommend this course to another student? Please explain.
comments: This course is awesome and I definitely recommend it!! It's more of a critical thinking course and "what are your thoughts and critiques" rather than just sitting back and learning. you're exposed to a lot of different materials and forms of dance. absolutely loved it
Yes! I think it was material I havent been able to learn in other classes that is still crucial to know!

Yes! It is a good and interesting introduction to dance studies and is not too much work.  Prof. Reid is amazing - she's very kind, funny, and passionate about the field, making it more interesting to learn about.
